WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.383 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:04.383 --> 00:00:16.050 align:middle line:90%


00:00:16.050 --> 00:00:18.550 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA MEREDITH: One of the
most speculated about subjects

00:00:18.550 --> 00:00:21.040 align:middle line:84%
in modern Western history
has been whether or not

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:23.320 align:middle line:84%
humans live more
than one lifetime.

00:00:23.320 --> 00:00:25.120 align:middle line:10%
In the East, however,
reincarnation

00:00:25.120 --> 00:00:27.160 align:middle line:10%
is an accepted
phenomenon that is

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.920 align:middle line:10%
at the basis of many of the
world's oldest religions.

00:00:30.920 --> 00:00:33.380 align:middle line:10%
Since the West worships
science, it takes a scientist

00:00:33.380 --> 00:00:36.060 align:middle line:10%
to serve as a cultural
shaman in the understanding

00:00:36.060 --> 00:00:38.960 align:middle line:10%
of this esoteric subject,
and Paul Van Ward

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:40.690 align:middle line:10%
has put his Harvard
degree to use

00:00:40.690 --> 00:00:42.950 align:middle line:10%
to provide us with a
scientific framework

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:46.850 align:middle line:10%
for understanding reincarnation
in his book The Soul Genome.

00:00:46.850 --> 00:00:48.610 align:middle line:90%
And he joins us today.

00:00:48.610 --> 00:00:49.400 align:middle line:90%
Welcome, Paul.

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:51.024 align:middle line:90%
I love your jacket.

00:00:51.024 --> 00:00:51.800 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

00:00:51.800 --> 00:00:52.300 align:middle line:90%
>>PAUL VON WARD: Thank you.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:53.620 align:middle line:90%
I'm delighted to be here.

00:00:53.620 --> 00:00:55.340 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Who knows where
you were in another lifetime,

00:00:55.340 --> 00:00:55.580 align:middle line:90%
right?

00:00:55.580 --> 00:00:57.330 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: That's
right, this is royalty.

00:00:57.330 --> 00:00:58.670 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Flamboyant.

00:00:58.670 --> 00:01:01.050 align:middle line:84%
One of the things I really
like about your book,

00:01:01.050 --> 00:01:02.474 align:middle line:84%
you go into a lot
of the science.

00:01:02.474 --> 00:01:04.640 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to get into
some of the science of it

00:01:04.640 --> 00:01:06.810 align:middle line:84%
today because I
think it's important.

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:09.690 align:middle line:84%
And you've spent many, many
years delving into this.

00:01:09.690 --> 00:01:12.110 align:middle line:84%
But I also would like to
spend some time getting

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:14.160 align:middle line:90%
into the examples.

00:01:14.160 --> 00:01:16.590 align:middle line:84%
And there is this
five factor evaluation

00:01:16.590 --> 00:01:18.800 align:middle line:84%
that you take into
consideration.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.220 align:middle line:84%
We'll get to that a little
bit later in the interview

00:01:21.220 --> 00:01:24.770 align:middle line:84%
with some really
tantalizing comparison

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:27.354 align:middle line:84%
photographs including
Marilyn Monroe.

00:01:27.354 --> 00:01:28.020 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Yes.

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:29.478 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And a
more recent version

00:01:29.478 --> 00:01:33.500 align:middle line:84%
of Marilyn Monroe, Gurdjieff
the mystic, and others.

00:01:33.500 --> 00:01:35.767 align:middle line:84%
And I just wanted
to let people know

00:01:35.767 --> 00:01:37.350 align:middle line:84%
that even though we
can't start there,

00:01:37.350 --> 00:01:38.310 align:middle line:90%
we're going to end up there.

00:01:38.310 --> 00:01:39.476 align:middle line:90%
And you've got to see these.

00:01:39.476 --> 00:01:40.620 align:middle line:90%
It's really mind blowing.

00:01:40.620 --> 00:01:42.420 align:middle line:84%
But first of all,
let's talk about you

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:45.530 align:middle line:84%
because you didn't
come by this naturally.

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:46.940 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Nope, I didn't.

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:49.460 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Baptist
minister, I mean, heavily

00:01:49.460 --> 00:01:52.350 align:middle line:84%
into the academic world
in your own studies.

00:01:52.350 --> 00:01:57.590 align:middle line:84%
Degree in Psychology from
Harvard, Naval officer, hello?

00:01:57.590 --> 00:01:59.270 align:middle line:84%
There's nothing in
here that speaks

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:01.190 align:middle line:84%
to writing books
on reincarnation

00:02:01.190 --> 00:02:03.130 align:middle line:90%
so tell us your story.

00:02:03.130 --> 00:02:06.130 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Well, you know,
I was born down in Florida

00:02:06.130 --> 00:02:11.030 align:middle line:84%
on a sharecropper's farm in the
end years of the Depression.

00:02:11.030 --> 00:02:16.820 align:middle line:10%
But here we are today, 70 years
plus later, and there we are.

00:02:16.820 --> 00:02:19.920 align:middle line:10%
I started out, really, in
a traditional sort of way,

00:02:19.920 --> 00:02:21.770 align:middle line:10%
you know, responding
to the culture

00:02:21.770 --> 00:02:26.390 align:middle line:10%
that I grew up in: the Southern
Baptist fundamentalist culture,

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:30.590 align:middle line:10%
university environment,
and following patrons.

00:02:30.590 --> 00:02:32.620 align:middle line:84%
You know, going
into the Navy, going

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:35.050 align:middle line:84%
to the diplomatic
service, following

00:02:35.050 --> 00:02:37.490 align:middle line:90%
the paths of older people.

00:02:37.490 --> 00:02:42.680 align:middle line:84%
But I think what happened, I
was working on my first effort

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:45.560 align:middle line:84%
at a degree in Clinical
Psychology at Florida State

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:48.610 align:middle line:84%
University, and I
was also part time

00:02:48.610 --> 00:02:50.690 align:middle line:84%
the minister for
the local church.

00:02:50.690 --> 00:02:56.370 align:middle line:84%
And Paul Tillich came, the great
theologian of the 20th century,

00:02:56.370 --> 00:02:59.150 align:middle line:84%
and we started
talking about God.

00:02:59.150 --> 00:03:01.780 align:middle line:84%
And I was a Southern
Baptist minister,

00:03:01.780 --> 00:03:06.420 align:middle line:84%
you know, and had a very
narrow specific idea of God.

00:03:06.420 --> 00:03:09.090 align:middle line:84%
And he had talked about
some expansive idea

00:03:09.090 --> 00:03:10.700 align:middle line:90%
and I said, how can you do that?

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:14.170 align:middle line:84%
He said, well, it's a matter
of how you define God.

00:03:14.170 --> 00:03:18.940 align:middle line:84%
Well, we had a little exchange
and it just opened my eyes up

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:23.510 align:middle line:84%
and I started moving out
of that traditional culture

00:03:23.510 --> 00:03:24.590 align:middle line:90%
that I was in.

00:03:24.590 --> 00:03:28.910 align:middle line:84%
And also, at the same
time, in clinical classes

00:03:28.910 --> 00:03:32.700 align:middle line:84%
and psychological
developmental classes,

00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:34.580 align:middle line:84%
you know, I started
very much interested

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:37.227 align:middle line:84%
in Carl Jung, rather
than the other folks

00:03:37.227 --> 00:03:38.310 align:middle line:90%
that I should be studying.

00:03:38.310 --> 00:03:38.976 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:03:38.976 --> 00:03:41.020 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: And so I
realized at that time

00:03:41.020 --> 00:03:42.400 align:middle line:90%
I was really on the wrong track.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:45.775 align:middle line:84%
So that's when I joined
the Navy to see the world

00:03:45.775 --> 00:03:48.170 align:middle line:84%
and went to officer
candidate school

00:03:48.170 --> 00:03:52.701 align:middle line:84%
just in time for the Cuban
Missile Crisis, and Vietnam,

00:03:52.701 --> 00:03:53.200 align:middle line:90%
and so on.

00:03:53.200 --> 00:03:57.400 align:middle line:84%
But fortunately, I was picked
up as a diplomat foreign service

00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:59.670 align:middle line:90%
officer for a 15 year career.

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:03.210 align:middle line:84%
But I got tired of
bureaucracy because I

00:04:03.210 --> 00:04:04.960 align:middle line:84%
wanted to change
things and I was always

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:06.880 align:middle line:90%
looking at underlying questions.

00:04:06.880 --> 00:04:09.320 align:middle line:84%
And why shouldn't we do
it this way and that way.

00:04:09.320 --> 00:04:10.820 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Asking
too many questions.

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:11.690 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Asking
too many questions.

00:04:11.690 --> 00:04:13.120 align:middle line:84%
And, in fact, the
State Department

00:04:13.120 --> 00:04:15.075 align:middle line:84%
paid for me to go
to spend a year up

00:04:15.075 --> 00:04:18.480 align:middle line:84%
at Harvard studying these sort
of psychological questions

00:04:18.480 --> 00:04:21.100 align:middle line:84%
of organizations
and how societies

00:04:21.100 --> 00:04:22.660 align:middle line:84%
work and all of
that sort of thing.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.020 align:middle line:84%
That would be
appropriate for what

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:27.860 align:middle line:84%
I thought my work in
the diplomatic service

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:29.640 align:middle line:90%
might involve.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:31.200 align:middle line:84%
And when I made
some recommendations

00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:36.360 align:middle line:84%
to make the Department
of State run better,

00:04:36.360 --> 00:04:38.170 align:middle line:84%
Henry Kissinger and
people like that--

00:04:38.170 --> 00:04:41.690 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: They're always
open to suggestions, right?

00:04:41.690 --> 00:04:44.230 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: I've realized after
running into that obstacle

00:04:44.230 --> 00:04:49.720 align:middle line:84%
that I didn't have a real
creative future in the State

00:04:49.720 --> 00:04:53.030 align:middle line:84%
Department, so I left and
started this track, really.

00:04:53.030 --> 00:04:56.680 align:middle line:84%
I founded and ran an
international nonprofit

00:04:56.680 --> 00:04:59.940 align:middle line:84%
for about 15 years to get the
kids through school and college

00:04:59.940 --> 00:05:00.910 align:middle line:90%
and that sort of thing.

00:05:00.910 --> 00:05:05.884 align:middle line:84%
And work on Soviet-American
citizen exchanges

00:05:05.884 --> 00:05:06.550 align:middle line:90%
and all of that.

00:05:06.550 --> 00:05:07.330 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:05:07.330 --> 00:05:09.770 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: It was
very worthwhile work.

00:05:09.770 --> 00:05:14.940 align:middle line:84%
But all the time, I was
thinking about these paranormal

00:05:14.940 --> 00:05:20.000 align:middle line:84%
psychological consciousness
questions and issues,

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.590 align:middle line:84%
and began to delve
into regressions

00:05:25.590 --> 00:05:30.390 align:middle line:84%
and learned to do that for
myself, and work with others.

00:05:30.390 --> 00:05:36.300 align:middle line:84%
And I began to just discover
a totally different world.

00:05:36.300 --> 00:05:38.570 align:middle line:84%
And met Ian Stevenson
at a conference

00:05:38.570 --> 00:05:40.670 align:middle line:84%
where we were talking
and, of course,

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:44.040 align:middle line:84%
he was the most eminent
scientific person

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:45.846 align:middle line:90%
to even deal with this issue.

00:05:45.846 --> 00:05:47.970 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: With past lives
in children in particular

00:05:47.970 --> 00:05:48.860 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Past
lives in children.

00:05:48.860 --> 00:05:49.740 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:05:49.740 --> 00:05:52.270 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: And his
focus was on memories

00:05:52.270 --> 00:05:57.790 align:middle line:84%
that survived death and
continued to be alive,

00:05:57.790 --> 00:06:00.990 align:middle line:90%
and the children who had them.

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:04.880 align:middle line:84%
And that was a
foundational area of work.

00:06:04.880 --> 00:06:09.200 align:middle line:84%
But my interest was in
developmental psychology.

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:10.401 align:middle line:90%
Where do we go?

00:06:10.401 --> 00:06:10.900 align:middle line:90%
From--

00:06:10.900 --> 00:06:12.540 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: How do we
become what we are?

00:06:12.540 --> 00:06:16.860 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: How do we become
what we are and-- so my focus

00:06:16.860 --> 00:06:20.710 align:middle line:84%
on reincarnation
research several years

00:06:20.710 --> 00:06:23.420 align:middle line:84%
later, after having talked
with him about his work

00:06:23.420 --> 00:06:27.060 align:middle line:84%
and getting more
interested in it myself,

00:06:27.060 --> 00:06:31.770 align:middle line:84%
I looked at stories
from different people.

00:06:31.770 --> 00:06:37.730 align:middle line:84%
About who seemed to have same
physical features, people

00:06:37.730 --> 00:06:40.400 align:middle line:90%
who had--

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:44.010 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Same physical
features as what?

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.540 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Well, all
physical features.

00:06:46.540 --> 00:06:49.340 align:middle line:90%
But the primary areas--

00:06:49.340 --> 00:06:51.739 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Well, I'm asking
in comparison to what?

00:06:51.739 --> 00:06:53.280 align:middle line:84%
They had the same
physical features--

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:53.575 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Oh, I'm sorry.

00:06:53.575 --> 00:06:54.190 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --in
comparison to what?

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:55.110 align:middle line:90%
Just for the context.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:55.860 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Right.

00:06:55.860 --> 00:06:56.712 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yeah.

00:06:56.712 --> 00:06:58.670 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: I just jumped
with that assumption.

00:06:58.670 --> 00:07:01.420 align:middle line:84%
We were talking about
comparing the features

00:07:01.420 --> 00:07:05.040 align:middle line:84%
of a person alive
today with any images

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:08.337 align:middle line:84%
we have of the alleged
previous lifetime.

00:07:08.337 --> 00:07:10.670 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And was that kind
of an original hook for you?

00:07:10.670 --> 00:07:12.790 align:middle line:90%
Was just these observations?

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:14.070 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: No.

00:07:14.070 --> 00:07:17.810 align:middle line:84%
Actually, Ian Stevenson
found in some of his cases

00:07:17.810 --> 00:07:20.167 align:middle line:90%
this sort of correspondence.

00:07:20.167 --> 00:07:20.750 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:24.760 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: And Walter Semkiw
who was following somewhat

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:30.550 align:middle line:84%
in the shoes of Ian
Stevens, as well,

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:35.060 align:middle line:84%
saw likenesses that he
would compare cases with.

00:07:35.060 --> 00:07:39.590 align:middle line:84%
So what I did to take that
sort of scientific step

00:07:39.590 --> 00:07:44.700 align:middle line:84%
to the next level was to
use biometric dimensions,

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:48.484 align:middle line:84%
technology, we use
cameras now and--

00:07:48.484 --> 00:07:50.150 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Oh yeah,
iris scans, all of it

00:07:50.150 --> 00:07:53.650 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Computers to
measure all of this stuff.

00:07:53.650 --> 00:07:57.120 align:middle line:84%
Iris scans is another
question because iris scans

00:07:57.120 --> 00:08:02.810 align:middle line:84%
seem to be a very idiosyncratic
part of our anatomy.

00:08:02.810 --> 00:08:03.415 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:08:03.415 --> 00:08:06.730 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: But our facial
architecture, our genotypes

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:10.920 align:middle line:84%
and so on seem to be part of
this reincarnation process.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:14.730 align:middle line:84%
So what I did was
to take a more,

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:18.660 align:middle line:84%
I say this is a self-serving
way, but a more systematic,

00:08:18.660 --> 00:08:24.090 align:middle line:84%
more quantitative approach than
Ian Stevenson or Walter Semkiw,

00:08:24.090 --> 00:08:26.750 align:middle line:90%
or Adrian Finkelstein.

00:08:26.750 --> 00:08:28.410 align:middle line:84%
We'll talk about
one of his cases.

00:08:28.410 --> 00:08:28.990 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK.

00:08:28.990 --> 00:08:31.230 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Which we took
to another level with him

00:08:31.230 --> 00:08:33.000 align:middle line:90%
in my collaboration with Adrian.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:33.549 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: OK

00:08:33.549 --> 00:08:36.600 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: So that was my--
and that came out of work

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:40.679 align:middle line:84%
I did at Harvard with
David McClelland who

00:08:40.679 --> 00:08:44.540 align:middle line:84%
was a social psychologist,
but we had worked together

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:50.470 align:middle line:84%
on his theory of how you infer
personality traits, how you

00:08:50.470 --> 00:08:54.650 align:middle line:84%
infer the underlying
personalities of people

00:08:54.650 --> 00:08:58.090 align:middle line:84%
from their written word,
from their spoken words.

00:08:58.090 --> 00:09:02.530 align:middle line:84%
So that led me to take
this developmental model

00:09:02.530 --> 00:09:04.201 align:middle line:84%
that I call the
Five Factor Model.

00:09:04.201 --> 00:09:05.700 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: To give
it this framework.

00:09:05.700 --> 00:09:08.560 align:middle line:84%
And one of the things you
were personally intrigued with

00:09:08.560 --> 00:09:10.810 align:middle line:90%
was the notion of prodigies.

00:09:10.810 --> 00:09:16.440 align:middle line:84%
How does someone come along that
can essentially compose music

00:09:16.440 --> 00:09:18.490 align:middle line:84%
by the age of four when
their fingers can't even

00:09:18.490 --> 00:09:20.670 align:middle line:84%
reach the keys yet and
they've had no training?

00:09:20.670 --> 00:09:23.450 align:middle line:84%
Who can speak multiple
languages and so forth.

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:26.650 align:middle line:84%
And one example-- we'll just
give a little one right upfront

00:09:26.650 --> 00:09:29.280 align:middle line:90%
here-- was that of Paul Gauguin.

00:09:29.280 --> 00:09:33.410 align:middle line:84%
And what is believed to be his
more recent incarnation, which

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:35.665 align:middle line:84%
is, what is
Teekamp's first name?

00:09:35.665 --> 00:09:36.980 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: It's Peter Teekamp.

00:09:36.980 --> 00:09:37.980 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Peter Teekamp.

00:09:37.980 --> 00:09:39.690 align:middle line:10%
And let's take a look at that.

00:09:39.690 --> 00:09:41.100 align:middle line:10%
We see the two people.

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.330 align:middle line:10%
Now this was Gauguin.

00:09:42.330 --> 00:09:43.913 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: Well,
this is Paul Gauguin

00:09:43.913 --> 00:09:46.170 align:middle line:10%
and his wife, Motte Gauguin.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:53.694 align:middle line:10%
And they were, of course,
known as a couple.

00:09:53.694 --> 00:09:54.360 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:09:54.360 --> 00:09:55.860 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: Since
they were married.

00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:57.910 align:middle line:10%
But he, of course,
left her very early on

00:09:57.910 --> 00:10:00.640 align:middle line:10%
and went on a wanderlust
kind of sort of life.

00:10:00.640 --> 00:10:02.806 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Yeah, he had a
wild kind of streak in him.

00:10:02.806 --> 00:10:04.882 align:middle line:10%
And let's look at
the next image now.

00:10:04.882 --> 00:10:06.340 align:middle line:84%
Well, here, let's
look at this one.

00:10:06.340 --> 00:10:08.900 align:middle line:84%
We don't have the one
of the two side by side,

00:10:08.900 --> 00:10:11.820 align:middle line:84%
but this one is really, to
me, one of my favorite images

00:10:11.820 --> 00:10:12.320 align:middle line:90%
you have.

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:14.486 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Well, this is
very interesting because--

00:10:14.486 --> 00:10:20.410 align:middle line:84%
and I have to make it clear that
Peter Teekamp and his partner,

00:10:20.410 --> 00:10:24.510 align:middle line:84%
they're not married, but
Michelle Moshier actually

00:10:24.510 --> 00:10:27.590 align:middle line:90%
did this research on their own.

00:10:27.590 --> 00:10:29.230 align:middle line:90%
I didn't do it.

00:10:29.230 --> 00:10:32.230 align:middle line:84%
Stevenson or Semkiw
or no one else did.

00:10:32.230 --> 00:10:34.430 align:middle line:84%
All of us have looked
at it, obviously,

00:10:34.430 --> 00:10:36.180 align:middle line:90%
to demonstrate it as a case.

00:10:36.180 --> 00:10:37.890 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: And what
we're looking at here,

00:10:37.890 --> 00:10:40.950 align:middle line:10%
the research is, we're looking
at the work on the left hand

00:10:40.950 --> 00:10:43.734 align:middle line:10%
side, Gauguin, which
has age groups on it,

00:10:43.734 --> 00:10:45.150 align:middle line:10%
and then we're
looking at the work

00:10:45.150 --> 00:10:46.632 align:middle line:10%
on the right which is Teekamp.

00:10:46.632 --> 00:10:47.340 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: Yeah.

00:10:47.340 --> 00:10:48.714 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: Now
Teekamp was already

00:10:48.714 --> 00:10:51.250 align:middle line:10%
recognized for his artistic
abilities by the age of five.

00:10:51.250 --> 00:10:53.780 align:middle line:10%
It took Gauguin considerably
longer to become recognized.

00:10:53.780 --> 00:10:54.053 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: Oh yes.

00:10:54.053 --> 00:10:54.552 align:middle line:10%
Yeah.

00:10:54.552 --> 00:10:58.250 align:middle line:10%
Teekamp sort of made
friends in this school

00:10:58.250 --> 00:11:01.000 align:middle line:10%
because he could draw
the classmates' face.

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:03.450 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: But look at
the subject matters.

00:11:03.450 --> 00:11:05.530 align:middle line:10%
Teekamp did not know
of Gauguin's work

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:06.959 align:middle line:10%
and the correlation
between them.

00:11:06.959 --> 00:11:08.250 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: No, he had no idea.

00:11:08.250 --> 00:11:09.185 align:middle line:10%
He never had even heard of him.

00:11:09.185 --> 00:11:10.576 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: But they're
doing the same subjects.

00:11:10.576 --> 00:11:11.867 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: Had no sense of it.

00:11:11.867 --> 00:11:15.990 align:middle line:10%
Well, it's not so much
in these comparisons, not

00:11:15.990 --> 00:11:18.080 align:middle line:10%
the artistic skill itself.

00:11:18.080 --> 00:11:19.335 align:middle line:10%
It is actually--

00:11:19.335 --> 00:11:19.830 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: It's the subject.

00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:20.530 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: --the
subject matter.

00:11:20.530 --> 00:11:21.863 align:middle line:10%
>>REGINA: It's a subject matter.

00:11:21.863 --> 00:11:24.470 align:middle line:10%
>>VON WARD: And so
here he is painting

00:11:24.470 --> 00:11:31.010 align:middle line:10%
100 years later similar
subjects at an earlier age.

00:11:31.010 --> 00:11:35.130 align:middle line:10%
And this is what we use
as an example of, sort of,

00:11:35.130 --> 00:11:36.265 align:middle line:10%
the evolutionary process.

00:11:36.265 --> 00:11:41.770 align:middle line:10%
Because it took-- Because
Gauguin, of course,

00:11:41.770 --> 00:11:45.650 align:middle line:10%
didn't start his art until
he was in his mid 20s.

00:11:45.650 --> 00:11:48.690 align:middle line:84%
And so here we have a
case where he's just

00:11:48.690 --> 00:11:51.490 align:middle line:84%
doing it automatically
from the beginning.

00:11:51.490 --> 00:11:55.460 align:middle line:84%
And we see this in
music, mathematics, art,

00:11:55.460 --> 00:11:57.780 align:middle line:90%
in Tiger Woods, and golf.

00:11:57.780 --> 00:11:58.860 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes!

00:11:58.860 --> 00:12:04.950 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: So all of
these precocities--

00:12:04.950 --> 00:12:08.650 align:middle line:84%
I like to use the word precocity
because all people have

00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:11.200 align:middle line:84%
precocity in one
area or the other.

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:13.640 align:middle line:84%
And there's no
explanation for it.

00:12:13.640 --> 00:12:16.970 align:middle line:84%
Noam Chomsky talked
about language

00:12:16.970 --> 00:12:24.220 align:middle line:84%
even that we come already with
the structures of our language

00:12:24.220 --> 00:12:25.034 align:middle line:90%
in--

00:12:25.034 --> 00:12:25.700 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Yes.

00:12:25.700 --> 00:12:26.560 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: --our inheritance.

00:12:26.560 --> 00:12:26.880 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes, yes.

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:28.650 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: So this inheritance.

00:12:28.650 --> 00:12:30.150 align:middle line:90%
Where does it come from?

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:35.200 align:middle line:84%
It's not something that's
developed in accord

00:12:35.200 --> 00:12:38.200 align:middle line:84%
with a model that
psychologists use today.

00:12:38.200 --> 00:12:39.640 align:middle line:84%
You learn it from
the environment,

00:12:39.640 --> 00:12:41.099 align:middle line:84%
you get reinforcement,
all of that.

00:12:41.099 --> 00:12:42.515 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: No because
in that case,

00:12:42.515 --> 00:12:44.880 align:middle line:84%
you would see within families
very similar personality

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:47.002 align:middle line:84%
traits, behaviors,
propensities, and precocities.

00:12:47.002 --> 00:12:47.960 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Absolutely.

00:12:47.960 --> 00:12:49.360 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But you
don't see that.

00:12:49.360 --> 00:12:51.209 align:middle line:84%
We're each very
individual regardless--

00:12:51.209 --> 00:12:52.750 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Regardless
of the family.

00:12:52.750 --> 00:12:54.050 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --of that
nature nurture part.

00:12:54.050 --> 00:12:55.310 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Some of them
are in the same family.

00:12:55.310 --> 00:12:57.670 align:middle line:84%
I mean musicians in the
same family and so on.

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:02.424 align:middle line:84%
But those are just
exceptions, you know?

00:13:02.424 --> 00:13:03.090 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Right.

00:13:03.090 --> 00:13:04.548 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Because
most people are

00:13:04.548 --> 00:13:07.532 align:middle line:84%
different from their family in
terms of the area of precocity.

00:13:07.532 --> 00:13:08.490 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Very much so.

00:13:08.490 --> 00:13:11.110 align:middle line:90%
Very unique.

00:13:11.110 --> 00:13:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And one of the-- Carol
Bowman, continued on.

00:13:14.490 --> 00:13:17.180 align:middle line:84%
She did similar work
to Stevenson's, but she

00:13:17.180 --> 00:13:18.930 align:middle line:84%
was working with the
children directly

00:13:18.930 --> 00:13:21.280 align:middle line:90%
and I love some of the examples.

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:23.200 align:middle line:84%
You bring up her
work in your book,

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:24.620 align:middle line:90%
but you have others as well.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:27.880 align:middle line:84%
But let's, again, by
example because I learn well

00:13:27.880 --> 00:13:28.640 align:middle line:90%
by example.

00:13:28.640 --> 00:13:29.880 align:middle line:90%
So I like examples.

00:13:29.880 --> 00:13:34.552 align:middle line:84%
But let's talk about the Indian
man with the shortened fingers.

00:13:34.552 --> 00:13:35.260 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Sure.

00:13:35.260 --> 00:13:36.160 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Can you
give an example

00:13:36.160 --> 00:13:38.185 align:middle line:84%
of how something carries
forward as a trauma

00:13:38.185 --> 00:13:39.310 align:middle line:90%
even from another lifetime?

00:13:39.310 --> 00:13:42.390 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Well, this is one of
Ian Stevenson's most well-known

00:13:42.390 --> 00:13:48.310 align:middle line:84%
cases because he had observed
that certain features could

00:13:48.310 --> 00:13:51.450 align:middle line:84%
carry forth from one
lifetime to another

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:53.590 align:middle line:90%
or appear to carry forward.

00:13:53.590 --> 00:13:56.130 align:middle line:84%
But this is a case where
you had an accident

00:13:56.130 --> 00:13:58.940 align:middle line:90%
at the end of a lifetime.

00:13:58.940 --> 00:14:03.560 align:middle line:84%
Where a person's fingers
were mangled and cut off.

00:14:03.560 --> 00:14:07.650 align:middle line:84%
And yet, you still
had some carry forward

00:14:07.650 --> 00:14:14.330 align:middle line:84%
in the genes that left you
with a disfigured, deformed

00:14:14.330 --> 00:14:15.890 align:middle line:90%
same area of the body.

00:14:15.890 --> 00:14:21.040 align:middle line:84%
I had a case in this with
Claus von Stauffenberg case

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:24.470 align:middle line:84%
and the person who
may be likely to be

00:14:24.470 --> 00:14:28.910 align:middle line:84%
the reincarnation of Claus von
Stauffenberg who had problems

00:14:28.910 --> 00:14:37.270 align:middle line:84%
on his fingers, in his eye, on
his back that are coincident

00:14:37.270 --> 00:14:40.330 align:middle line:84%
with the injuries of
Claus von Stauffenberg.

00:14:40.330 --> 00:14:42.480 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Which is really,
I mean this brings up,

00:14:42.480 --> 00:14:44.389 align:middle line:90%
this begs a lot of questions.

00:14:44.389 --> 00:14:46.430 align:middle line:84%
And this is right down to
birthmarks on the body.

00:14:46.430 --> 00:14:48.860 align:middle line:84%
Simple things that
all of us carry.

00:14:48.860 --> 00:14:53.170 align:middle line:84%
A marking here or maybe a
propensity or weakness there.

00:14:53.170 --> 00:14:57.690 align:middle line:84%
That may be an imprint
that's carried forward

00:14:57.690 --> 00:15:00.210 align:middle line:84%
through the soul portion
of our being and imprints

00:15:00.210 --> 00:15:02.110 align:middle line:90%
on the DNA of our bodies.

00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:04.800 align:middle line:84%
So it's not just
extraordinary things.

00:15:04.800 --> 00:15:07.050 align:middle line:84%
You can probably find
something on your own body--

00:15:07.050 --> 00:15:07.350 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Sure.

00:15:07.350 --> 00:15:09.790 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: --that may have
been a remnant or an artifact

00:15:09.790 --> 00:15:11.920 align:middle line:84%
of something that had
happened from another time.

00:15:11.920 --> 00:15:14.870 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: And different
figures, figurations

00:15:14.870 --> 00:15:17.690 align:middle line:84%
in your face and so
on may carry forward.

00:15:17.690 --> 00:15:21.330 align:middle line:84%
But there's the
underlying bone structure

00:15:21.330 --> 00:15:23.520 align:middle line:84%
which seems to be
carried forward.

00:15:23.520 --> 00:15:27.260 align:middle line:84%
And we use the
biometric dimensions

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:31.007 align:middle line:84%
to measure our architecture
of our bone structure.

00:15:31.007 --> 00:15:32.340 align:middle line:90%
And that seems to carry forward.

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:34.830 align:middle line:84%
But then what is
interesting about the fact

00:15:34.830 --> 00:15:38.460 align:middle line:84%
that it's a wound in
the past life that gets

00:15:38.460 --> 00:15:41.076 align:middle line:84%
carried forward in
some other form,

00:15:41.076 --> 00:15:42.450 align:middle line:84%
but in the same
part of the body.

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:47.540 align:middle line:84%
Now this suggests something
about the psychoplasm

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:50.817 align:middle line:84%
or the soul genome
carrying information--

00:15:50.817 --> 00:15:51.400 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:15:51.400 --> 00:15:54.950 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: --that there
is some deformation that

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:59.720 align:middle line:84%
occurred at the end of life
or near the end of life which

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:03.080 align:middle line:84%
somehow goes as part
of the epigenome that

00:16:03.080 --> 00:16:08.670 align:middle line:84%
is the information around
the specific physical genes

00:16:08.670 --> 00:16:11.530 align:middle line:84%
that somehow affect
this new body.

00:16:11.530 --> 00:16:12.847 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: That inform the DNA.

00:16:12.847 --> 00:16:13.930 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: That informs--

00:16:13.930 --> 00:16:15.660 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And I mean,
then we're talking--

00:16:15.660 --> 00:16:17.500 align:middle line:84%
I wasn't going to get
into it at this point,

00:16:17.500 --> 00:16:21.610 align:middle line:84%
but you're talking
about this 95% junk DNA.

00:16:21.610 --> 00:16:22.460 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Yeah.

00:16:22.460 --> 00:16:24.796 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: That the human
being supposedly drags around

00:16:24.796 --> 00:16:25.296 align:middle line:90%
with us.

00:16:25.296 --> 00:16:25.670 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Right.

00:16:25.670 --> 00:16:27.628 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And this puts
a little different spin

00:16:27.628 --> 00:16:29.316 align:middle line:84%
on what may be actually
going on there.

00:16:29.316 --> 00:16:30.440 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: No, absolutely.

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:32.780 align:middle line:84%
And we don't even
know whether it

00:16:32.780 --> 00:16:36.080 align:middle line:84%
is the junk DNA
or the information

00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:39.044 align:middle line:90%
field which encompasses--

00:16:39.044 --> 00:16:40.210 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Permeates or yeah.

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:41.126 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Permeates.

00:16:41.126 --> 00:16:46.460 align:middle line:84%
Because when you have a physical
feature of any kind that

00:16:46.460 --> 00:16:51.030 align:middle line:84%
has been expressed
by DNA, the genes

00:16:51.030 --> 00:16:55.710 align:middle line:84%
that are appropriate for that
part of your body, what happens

00:16:55.710 --> 00:16:58.780 align:middle line:84%
is regardless of the
gene itself that you

00:16:58.780 --> 00:17:04.400 align:middle line:84%
might bring from your
parent, it is a question

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:07.190 align:middle line:84%
of what actually makes it
express one way or the other.

00:17:07.190 --> 00:17:10.030 align:middle line:84%
And that's where I think we're
talking about consciousness

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:14.790 align:middle line:84%
as part of the soul
genome that activates

00:17:14.790 --> 00:17:15.957 align:middle line:90%
the expression of the genes.

00:17:15.957 --> 00:17:18.165 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: And you're getting
into Bruce Lipton's work

00:17:18.165 --> 00:17:19.660 align:middle line:84%
in epigenetics
quite a bit there.

00:17:19.660 --> 00:17:21.864 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: Yeah, I mean,
what we're learning--

00:17:21.864 --> 00:17:23.280 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Not his
work, but I mean

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:24.760 align:middle line:84%
his work expresses part
of what you're saying.

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:26.609 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: It's the
same area of science

00:17:26.609 --> 00:17:32.280 align:middle line:84%
that is fascinating now because
we know that information that

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:39.480 align:middle line:84%
is consciousness or intention
or some sort of energetic field

00:17:39.480 --> 00:17:41.800 align:middle line:84%
that's not quite in our
three dimensional field.

00:17:41.800 --> 00:17:44.107 align:middle line:84%
That's why I call it
the four dimensional.

00:17:44.107 --> 00:17:44.690 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:17:44.690 --> 00:17:46.340 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: You know,
because it's something

00:17:46.340 --> 00:17:47.800 align:middle line:84%
that the Russians
have been dealing

00:17:47.800 --> 00:17:50.360 align:middle line:84%
with for some time
trying to figure out

00:17:50.360 --> 00:17:53.110 align:middle line:84%
this energetic field
that encompasses

00:17:53.110 --> 00:17:57.830 align:middle line:90%
our physical biofield.

00:17:57.830 --> 00:18:07.990 align:middle line:84%
So we've got now this new area
in science which, in my view,

00:18:07.990 --> 00:18:11.660 align:middle line:84%
underpins our
reincarnation theories.

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:13.532 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: Yes, it
makes perfect sense.

00:18:13.532 --> 00:18:14.740 align:middle line:90%
You're talking about fields--

00:18:14.740 --> 00:18:15.510 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: There's a mechanism.

00:18:15.510 --> 00:18:16.410 align:middle line:90%
>>REGINA: Yes.

00:18:16.410 --> 00:18:19.770 align:middle line:84%
And one of the examples I
remember in Bruce's work

00:18:19.770 --> 00:18:23.970 align:middle line:84%
was that he was talking
about an environment in utero

00:18:23.970 --> 00:18:29.310 align:middle line:84%
where a child was going to
be born into a family that

00:18:29.310 --> 00:18:31.540 align:middle line:84%
had a fair amount of
domestic violence.

00:18:31.540 --> 00:18:33.740 align:middle line:84%
And in response
to this, the child

00:18:33.740 --> 00:18:38.440 align:middle line:84%
came out with a thicker
skull than was possessed

00:18:38.440 --> 00:18:39.940 align:middle line:84%
by the other members
of the family

00:18:39.940 --> 00:18:45.010 align:middle line:84%
by the previous generation
in the attempt to,

00:18:45.010 --> 00:18:47.270 align:middle line:84%
he was extrapolating,
but this was

00:18:47.270 --> 00:18:50.210 align:middle line:84%
to be able to protect itself
against the future violence

00:18:50.210 --> 00:18:51.310 align:middle line:90%
that was going to come.

00:18:51.310 --> 00:18:54.020 align:middle line:84%
Now you have a lot of questions
that are embedded in that.

00:18:54.020 --> 00:18:56.170 align:middle line:84%
Why would a soul choose
such a situation?

00:18:56.170 --> 00:18:59.056 align:middle line:84%
Then to be able to
also-- which has

00:18:59.056 --> 00:19:00.680 align:middle line:84%
very good reasons we
would choose that.

00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:01.970 align:middle line:84%
That might be our
group that we've

00:19:01.970 --> 00:19:03.470 align:middle line:84%
been working things
out with, right?

00:19:03.470 --> 00:19:04.440 align:middle line:90%
We'll get into that.

00:19:04.440 --> 00:19:05.450 align:middle line:84%
>>VON WARD: That's
another question.

00:19:05.450 --> 00:19:07.741 align:middle line:84%
>>REGINA: But then just to
affect the DNA to the extent

00:19:07.741 --> 00:19:10.502 align:middle line:84%
that you can thicken the skull
while in utero, in development.

00:19:10.502 --> 00:19:11.210 align:middle line:90%
>>VON WARD: Yeah.

00:19:11.210 --> 00:19:13.340 align:middle line:84%
Well, this brings to
the point-- I'll just

00:19:13.340 --> 00:19:14.700 align:middle line:90%
make a short point here.

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:18.020 align:middle line:84%
Because we have a
theoretical question

00:19:18.020 --> 00:19:21.390 align:middle line:84%
of when does the soul
genome or psychoplasm

00:19:21.390 --> 00:19:25.580 align:middle line:84%
engage in the zygote
process of development?

00:19:25.580 --> 00:19:27.510 align:middle line:84%
And it seems to me
that if we're talking

00:19:27.510 --> 00:19:30.070 align:middle line:84%
about these energetic fields
and information fields

00:19:30.070 --> 00:19:34.000 align:middle line:84%
that it is likely to happen
